n":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":65,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":74,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Henry Blackburn was born about 1150, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England. He had at least 3 sons. He lived in Rishton, Lancashire, England in 1245. He died in 1230, in Blackburn, Lancashire, England, at the age of 81."},"et":{"about 1150–by 1230":"umbes 1150–1230","1175–1238":"1175–1238","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1189–Male":"1189–Surnud","1150–1230":"1150–1230","about 1150":"umbes 1150","by 1230":"1230","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","Blackburn, Lancashire, England":"Blackburn, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"abo